comments.body:
`_io.TextIOWrapper` methods are protected by critical sections. Example with write:

```
/*[clinic input]
@critical_section
_io.TextIOWrapper.write
```

It's used to make these methods atomic. For example, it's safe to use `self->pending_bytes` without holding a dedicated lock on `self->pending_bytes`.

Then comes `tracemalloc` which injects hooks on memory allocations. `_io.TextIOWrapper.write()` calls `_io__Buffered_flush()` which calls `PyMemoryView_FromBuffer()` which calls indirectly `PyObject_Malloc()`. `tracemalloc` has a hook on `PyObject_Malloc()` and calls its `tracemalloc_alloc()` function which calls `tracemalloc` `TABLES_LOCK()`. If another thread is already holding the thread, `TABLES_LOCK()` can call `_PyThreadState_Detach()` which suspends the current critical section: `TextIOWrapper` critical section!

So while `tracemalloc` is running, it's possible that it unlocks the `TextIOWrapper` critical section and another thread can call a `TextIOWrapper` method concurrently!

In short, it's possible that `_io_TextIOWrapper_write()` runs in two threads in parallel, and so it's no longer safe to use `self->pending_bytes` without a dedicated lock.

Example from `Modules/_io/textio.c`:

```c
    else if (!PyList_CheckExact(self->pending_bytes)) {
        PyObject *list = PyList_New(2);
        if (list == NULL) {
            Py_DECREF(b);
            return NULL;
        }
        // Since Python 3.12, allocating GC object won't trigger GC and release
        // GIL. See https://github.com/python/cpython/issues/97922
        assert(!PyList_CheckExact(self->pending_bytes));
        PyList_SET_ITEM(list, 0, self->pending_bytes);
        PyList_SET_ITEM(list, 1, b);
        self->pending_bytes = list;
    }
```

The comment is interesting. When using `tracemalloc`, the comment is no longer true: allocation memory can release the GIL and suspend the critical section.

I'm not sure how to solve this problem.
